- Argument 2 stands out as it focuses on the income side (real wages increasing), which is a different mechanism (affordability due to higher income rather than lower prices).

However, even though Argument 2 is distinct, the other arguments (1, 3, 4, 5, 6) are not semantically disjoint among themselvesâ€”they all relate to cost reduction in some way. Therefore, there are pairs of arguments (e.g., 1 and 6, both about technological advancements) whose justifications are not semantically disjoint.

Result: false
Justification: Several pairs of arguments (e.g., those about cost reduction mechanisms) share overlapping semantic justifications (e.g., technology, policies, trade) that contribute to the claim, so they are not semantically disjoint. Only Argument 2 is disjoint from the others, but the others overlap.